1
00:00:01,640 --> 00:00:03,939
Good work.

2
00:00:03,940 --> 00:00:04,940
Um...

3
00:00:05,860 --> 00:00:08,649
Has the Takeichi Masaten
family contacted us?

4
00:00:08,650 --> 00:00:09,650
Oh...

5
00:00:10,020 --> 00:00:11,740
They haven't especialy reached out.

6
00:00:11,940 --> 00:00:13,380
Nothing today either.

7
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:15,310
Yeah.

8
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:27,090
Something that's always been there...

9
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:31,840
(Store Closing Notice)
Doesn't mean it'll be there forever.

10
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:36,330
I think there was one over there, too...

11
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:43,570
He's so handsome it's infuriating.

12
00:00:44,440 --> 00:00:45,440
Shizuka.

13
00:00:46,280 --> 00:00:48,399
- Sorry I'm late.
- No, it's fine.

14
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:49,400
Let's go.

15
00:00:52,500 --> 00:00:53,500
Shizuka?

16
00:01:30,300 --> 00:01:35,700
"Life In Smokey Blue"

17
00:01:36,220 --> 00:01:37,919
(Episode 8: Hope)
Is this a book club?

18
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:38,920
Yeah.

19
00:01:39,160 --> 00:01:40,060
I thought that besides our classes,

20
00:01:40,061 --> 00:01:42,440
it'd be nice to have
another place to learn.

21
00:01:43,170 --> 00:01:45,129
We're happy about it,

22
00:01:45,130 --> 00:01:47,170
but aren't you busy, sensei?

23
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:49,240
Well...

24
00:01:49,400 --> 00:01:51,079
Getting more books into the
hands of Japanese readers,

25
00:01:51,080 --> 00:01:52,136
even if it's just one more.

26
00:01:52,160 --> 00:01:54,300
I used to think that was my mission.

27
00:01:54,740 --> 00:01:57,349
But passing on the knowledge
and skills I've learned so far

28
00:01:57,350 --> 00:02:00,419
to your generation

29
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:02,220
is also an important part of my job.

30
00:02:02,920 --> 00:02:03,843
Passing it on...

31
00:02:03,867 --> 00:02:06,660
For the first meeting, I was thinking
we could discuss Nesbit's work.

32
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:08,760
I'll contact you with the details later.

33
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:11,980
Nesbit, huh? I'm looking forward to it.

34
00:02:12,160 --> 00:02:14,100
Are you a fan of hers?

35
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:17,170
When I was a kid, I was
captivated by the stories themselves.

36
00:02:17,230 --> 00:02:21,240
But as I got older, I often found
myself relating to the author.

37
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:24,340
I heard she went
through a lot of hardships.

38
00:02:24,670 --> 00:02:25,970
I see.

39
00:02:26,740 --> 00:02:28,980
Her various childhood memories

40
00:02:29,040 --> 00:02:31,680
seem to have become
the foundation of her work.

41
00:02:32,500 --> 00:02:34,249
In the face of a harsh reality,

42
00:02:34,250 --> 00:02:35,679
she might have been writing

43
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:39,350
to protect her own sense of belonging.

44
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:43,700
A sense of belonging...

45
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:46,880
I don't mind being alone.

46
00:02:48,420 --> 00:02:51,000
But family,

47
00:02:51,780 --> 00:02:52,780
lovers,

48
00:02:53,380 --> 00:02:54,440
friends,

49
00:02:55,070 --> 00:02:55,800
hobbies,

50
00:02:55,800 --> 00:02:56,800
work...

51
00:02:58,320 --> 00:03:01,000
I understand that feeling of
searching for something to hold on to.

52
00:03:02,700 --> 00:03:05,200
I also know the happiness
of being held by someone.

53
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:07,400
But...

54
00:03:08,160 --> 00:03:13,160
there's also the anxiety
and fear of losing it...

55
00:03:16,980 --> 00:03:20,700
I'd be lonely if you weren't here.

56
00:03:30,680 --> 00:03:35,040
It's lonely when someone's gone, isn't it?

57
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:40,720
Here, this is for you.
The berry tart you like, Shizuka.

58
00:03:41,260 --> 00:03:42,360
Thank you.

59
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:45,320
- You have a good memory.
- Of course I do.

60
00:03:45,840 --> 00:03:47,100
Minoru likes cheesecake.

61
00:03:47,540 --> 00:03:48,900
Sensei likes savory rice crackers.

62
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:52,260
And Mikami-san likes coffee jelly.

63
00:03:53,240 --> 00:03:54,440
I guess that's right.

64
00:03:55,520 --> 00:03:56,520
I'd completely forgotten.

65
00:03:57,480 --> 00:04:00,579
And also that when Nukita-san
brings someone's favorite food,

66
00:04:00,580 --> 00:04:02,480
you need to be on your guard.

67
00:04:04,480 --> 00:04:06,039
Since you understand that much,

68
00:04:06,040 --> 00:04:07,280
this should be easy.

69
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:22,860
Mm, what's this?

70
00:04:22,900 --> 00:04:23,900
Delicious.

71
00:04:24,060 --> 00:04:28,359
I hear it's a popular shop.
Editors always know the best places.

72
00:04:28,360 --> 00:04:29,560
Oh...

73
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:33,080
So that handsome older guy is an editor.

74
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:35,060
What do you mean, "that guy"?

75
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:40,110
Kuji Shizuka, you were on a
date last week, weren't you?

76
00:04:40,120 --> 00:04:41,680
With that handsome older guy.

77
00:04:42,740 --> 00:04:43,880
Huh?

78
00:04:44,320 --> 00:04:47,180
I actually happened to see
you two on the street last week.

79
00:04:47,250 --> 00:04:48,820
Why didn't you say hi?

80
00:04:49,590 --> 00:04:50,760
I was in a hurry.

81
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:53,140
But I'm surprised you recognized him.

82
00:04:53,220 --> 00:04:56,419
That the person from then
is the same one who brought this.

83
00:04:56,420 --> 00:04:57,960
It was the umbrella.

84
00:04:58,260 --> 00:04:59,260
Ah...

85
00:05:00,460 --> 00:05:01,560
Nukita-san.

86
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:03,040
He's very good at his job,

87
00:05:03,860 --> 00:05:05,100
but he's pretty clumsy.

88
00:05:06,020 --> 00:05:07,280
So his name is Nukita-san.

89
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:10,440
He's always losing his umbrellas,

90
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:12,499
so he deliberately picks
a color that stands out.

91
00:05:12,500 --> 00:05:13,500
Oh...

92
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:15,980
An ex-boyfriend?

93
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:18,649
He used to come to our house a lot.

94
00:05:18,650 --> 00:05:20,620
He was my father's editor back in the day.

95
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:24,719
Now that I've inherited the copyrights,

96
00:05:24,720 --> 00:05:25,960
we see each other occasionally.

97
00:05:26,220 --> 00:05:28,020
Oh...

98
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:31,320
Are you jealous?

99
00:05:31,720 --> 00:05:32,720
Of course not.

100
00:05:33,420 --> 00:05:35,340
You've got some nerve.

101
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:37,300
No, it just seemed like it.

102
00:05:38,330 --> 00:05:39,900
I'm glad if I was mistaken.

103
00:05:42,300 --> 00:05:44,040
Come here for a second.

104
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:56,290
Did you used to like him?

105
00:06:00,260 --> 00:06:01,260
I guess so.

106
00:06:02,260 --> 00:06:03,260
Probably.

107
00:06:03,380 --> 00:06:04,879
Probably?

108
00:06:04,880 --> 00:06:06,620
I was in middle school back then.

109
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:11,400
I had love, lust, and admiration
all mixed up.

110
00:06:11,770 --> 00:06:13,470
Oh...

111
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:15,370
That's pretty honest.

112
00:06:16,560 --> 00:06:18,840
I'm past the age of telling pointless lies.

113
00:06:20,740 --> 00:06:21,740
Well,

114
00:06:22,460 --> 00:06:24,360
I guess you're right.

115
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:29,360
I can understand how a
young Shizuka must have felt.

116
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:32,400
That guy is super charming.

117
00:06:33,220 --> 00:06:35,140
Seems like he's still got it.

118
00:06:36,380 --> 00:06:37,700
What do you mean, "still got it"?

119
00:06:37,940 --> 00:06:38,930
He's married.

120
00:06:38,930 --> 00:06:39,760
So?

121
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:45,100
And now he's reappeared in your life
as the editor for your father's work.

122
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:49,370
No wonder you looked so lost in thought.

123
00:06:50,010 --> 00:06:51,400
Lost in thought?

124
00:06:51,980 --> 00:06:53,400
Don't even try to deny it.

125
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:55,960
If that's how it looked, you're mistaken.

126
00:06:56,180 --> 00:06:57,780
How am I mistaken?

127
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:05,920
They're planning to release my father's
essays on translation as a paperback.

128
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:09,789
He asked if I would write an
essay for the end of the book.

129
00:07:09,790 --> 00:07:11,699
Oh, isn't that great?

130
00:07:11,700 --> 00:07:12,700
Is it?

131
00:07:14,330 --> 00:07:16,570
He said I could write about anything,

132
00:07:17,120 --> 00:07:19,200
but I have no idea what
to write or how to write it.

133
00:07:20,340 --> 00:07:25,340
True, "write about anything"
is the hardest prompt.

134
00:07:26,040 --> 00:07:28,440
Before that, when it comes to my father,

135
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:32,709
his work, and everything he taught me,

136
00:07:32,710 --> 00:07:34,980
I don't even know if I
want to write about it or not.

137
00:07:37,080 --> 00:07:38,780
Worrying over just a few pages.

138
00:07:40,020 --> 00:07:41,020
Oh...

139
00:07:42,920 --> 00:07:44,480
Since you're struggling with it,

140
00:07:45,080 --> 00:07:47,930
why not just give it a try?
That's one way to approach it, right?

141
00:07:50,360 --> 00:07:53,620
Regardless of whether
you publish what you write,

142
00:07:54,460 --> 00:07:56,339
once you start writing,

143
00:07:56,340 --> 00:07:58,740
you might be able to sort things out.

144
00:08:07,460 --> 00:08:10,020
Kuji Yoshiharu, the translator.

145
00:08:10,390 --> 00:08:12,350
And Kuji Yoshiharu, the father.

146
00:08:12,390 --> 00:08:15,620
The scent of the time
spent together in that study.

147
00:08:20,560 --> 00:08:21,560
Shizuka.

148
00:08:21,800 --> 00:08:22,800
Shizuka.

149
00:08:23,080 --> 00:08:26,300
Sensei said he was going to
the university. I tried to stop him,

150
00:08:26,340 --> 00:08:28,040
but he insisted he had a class to teach.

151
00:08:33,260 --> 00:08:35,280
I'll walk with him wherever he wants to go.

152
00:08:37,300 --> 00:08:38,300
It's okay.

153
00:08:39,480 --> 00:08:41,520
His steps are steadier than usual today.

154
00:08:43,060 --> 00:08:44,860
I'll be right by his side,
watching over him.

155
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:12,280
It's all gone now.

156
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:16,020
My sense of belonging here.

157
00:09:28,960 --> 00:09:30,370
Let's go home.

158
00:09:30,380 --> 00:09:31,800
Dad.

159
00:09:58,900 --> 00:10:00,260
I'm so glad.

160
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:03,019
It looks like your work has wrapped up.

161
00:10:03,020 --> 00:10:06,459
Yes, thank you so much
for your help back then.

162
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:09,770
Not at all. We should help
each other in times of need.

163
00:10:18,180 --> 00:10:19,550
Hara-san.

164
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:22,300
I'm sorry.

165
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:25,050
I suddenly remembered...

166
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:28,220
what happened during the earthquake...

167
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:32,500
I see.

168
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:34,700
Hara-san, you mean back in Miyagi...

169
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:39,000
Let's find a place to sit down and rest.

170
00:10:41,140 --> 00:10:43,270
Hara-san, are you okay?

171
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:49,140
Take your time. It's
okay to take your time.

172
00:10:51,380 --> 00:10:53,620
Hara-san, if you don't mind...

173
00:10:54,840 --> 00:10:56,650
I'm so sorry.

174
00:10:57,460 --> 00:10:59,380
It's been over ten years,

175
00:11:00,240 --> 00:11:02,420
but sometimes I still get like this.

176
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:08,200
But I'll be fine after
resting for a bit like this.

177
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,859
Azuma-san, please don't worry about me.

178
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:12,860
No.

179
00:11:13,640 --> 00:11:16,640
It seems the trains won't be
running for a while anyway.

180
00:11:18,060 --> 00:11:19,060
Oh no...

181
00:11:21,020 --> 00:11:22,950
What are we going to do...?

182
00:11:24,520 --> 00:11:25,520
Hara-san.

183
00:11:27,160 --> 00:11:28,259
I have a friend whose house

184
00:11:28,260 --> 00:11:30,620
is just a short walk from here.

185
00:11:31,880 --> 00:11:35,220
Can I call him and explain the situation?

186
00:11:36,680 --> 00:11:39,630
You could at least
rest there for the night.

187
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:46,069
He's a translator who mainly
works in the medical field.

188
00:11:46,070 --> 00:11:48,340
He's a trustworthy person.

189
00:11:51,080 --> 00:11:52,080
Um...

190
00:11:53,220 --> 00:11:55,210
I don't mean anything by it...

191
00:11:57,260 --> 00:12:01,140
I know someone like you, Azuma-san,
would never have any bad intentions.

192
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:04,690
And you can call me a
presumptuous old woman,

193
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:09,040
but I really can't go to a man's house.

194
00:12:10,950 --> 00:12:13,350
I'm sorry.

195
00:12:13,370 --> 00:12:14,570
How embarrassing.

196
00:12:15,790 --> 00:12:17,710
You were just worried about me.

197
00:12:18,710 --> 00:12:20,070
I'm truly sorry.

198
00:12:21,110 --> 00:12:22,110
Not at all.

199
00:12:22,830 --> 00:12:24,870
I'm the one who should be sorry.

200
00:12:25,630 --> 00:12:27,540
I was being thoughtless and insensitive.

201
00:12:29,630 --> 00:12:33,369
I'll go look for a 24-hour place
nearby.

202
00:12:33,370 --> 00:12:34,550
Wait here for a moment.

203
00:12:47,950 --> 00:12:49,050
Hello?

204
00:12:50,570 --> 00:12:53,000
It looks like the trains
are still out of service.

205
00:12:55,890 --> 00:12:57,510
Hara-san.

206
00:12:58,650 --> 00:13:02,010
I've looked, but every place is full.

207
00:13:02,310 --> 00:13:05,150
It looks like we still don't know
when the trains will be running again.

208
00:13:06,250 --> 00:13:10,830
I think it's best if you find
someplace warm to rest for the night.

209
00:13:13,570 --> 00:13:15,660
I contacted that friend
I mentioned earlier.

210
00:13:16,530 --> 00:13:18,260
He said you're welcome to come over.

211
00:13:21,790 --> 00:13:24,200
I know this might be a bit forward of me.

212
00:13:25,910 --> 00:13:29,810
But I consider you a very
important friend, Hara-san.

213
00:13:35,370 --> 00:13:38,880
I hope you can trust me.

214
00:13:43,090 --> 00:13:44,149
Huh?

215
00:13:44,150 --> 00:13:46,149
Is that Kuji Yoshiharu sensei?

216
00:13:46,150 --> 00:13:47,150
Yes.

217
00:13:47,730 --> 00:13:48,730
So...

218
00:13:49,050 --> 00:13:51,590
My father was the one who
first taught me literary translation.

219
00:13:52,390 --> 00:13:53,790
Oh, so that's how it is.

220
00:13:54,600 --> 00:13:58,800
I've read almost all of his translations.

221
00:14:04,530 --> 00:14:07,149
This one, for example,
when I was getting divorced...

222
00:14:07,150 --> 00:14:09,530
it brought me so much comfort.

223
00:14:16,110 --> 00:14:17,610
I've been divorced once.

224
00:14:18,450 --> 00:14:19,750
It's a bit embarrassing to say.

225
00:14:20,690 --> 00:14:22,010
There's nothing to be ashamed of.

226
00:14:23,410 --> 00:14:24,610
Everyone has their own story.

227
00:14:26,590 --> 00:14:27,790
That's true.

228
00:14:29,270 --> 00:14:30,270
Ah.

229
00:14:30,530 --> 00:14:32,810
Azuma, can you check on the pot for me?

230
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:34,340
Yeah, sure.

231
00:14:36,310 --> 00:14:37,510
Milk?

232
00:14:37,670 --> 00:14:38,770
That's unusual.

233
00:14:39,630 --> 00:14:40,980
Hm?

234
00:14:41,564 --> 00:14:43,691
(Receipt for milk)

235
00:14:45,030 --> 00:14:47,090
Is this for Hara-san...?

236
00:14:53,430 --> 00:14:54,610
This is delicious.

237
00:14:55,670 --> 00:14:57,230
I'm glad.

238
00:14:59,670 --> 00:15:02,230
I need to become stronger.

239
00:15:02,850 --> 00:15:04,290
Both mentally and physically.

240
00:15:06,190 --> 00:15:07,830
I can understand why you'd feel that way.

241
00:15:09,230 --> 00:15:13,110
But please don't push yourself too hard.

242
00:15:15,050 --> 00:15:17,590
You might think I'm
acting like I know it all,

243
00:15:18,730 --> 00:15:21,980
but I've been through something similar.

244
00:15:29,280 --> 00:15:30,960
You're right.

245
00:15:31,730 --> 00:15:32,730
Don't push yourself.

246
00:15:32,770 --> 00:15:33,770
Don't push yourself.

247
00:15:35,050 --> 00:15:36,719
No matter how hard you try,

248
00:15:36,720 --> 00:15:40,050
the ones who are gone won't come back.

249
00:15:42,210 --> 00:15:47,010
You just have to carry that
anxiety, sadness, and regret,

250
00:15:48,550 --> 00:15:51,580
and keep moving forward, right?

251
00:15:55,780 --> 00:15:58,720
For those of us who were
lucky enough to survive...

252
00:16:06,970 --> 00:16:08,789
Thank you so much for everything.

253
00:16:08,790 --> 00:16:10,370
Of course. Take care on your way.

254
00:16:10,400 --> 00:16:10,970
I will.

255
00:16:10,971 --> 00:16:12,790
Thanks. See you around.

256
00:16:15,210 --> 00:16:16,869
Yeah, about that thing...

257
00:16:16,870 --> 00:16:18,790
We'll talk later.

258
00:16:18,810 --> 00:16:19,810
Well, I'm off.

259
00:16:22,490 --> 00:16:25,630
See you.

260
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:31,650
Azuma-san and Kuji-san
are really close, aren't you?

261
00:16:32,770 --> 00:16:34,690
We used to push each other away.

262
00:16:35,250 --> 00:16:36,490
But he's a good person, really.

263
00:16:36,750 --> 00:16:37,750
He is.

264
00:16:38,550 --> 00:16:41,809
It's the first time I've seen
Azuma-san so relaxed.

265
00:16:41,810 --> 00:16:42,970
It's refreshing.

266
00:16:44,470 --> 00:16:47,390
You two have a great relationship.

267
00:16:48,610 --> 00:16:51,040
Hara-san, you may have already noticed,

268
00:16:51,630 --> 00:16:53,059
and if I just leave it as is,

269
00:16:53,060 --> 00:16:56,210
it wouldn't be fair to
let you keep wondering.

270
00:16:56,390 --> 00:16:57,680
So I'll just be direct.

271
00:16:58,750 --> 00:17:00,010
The thing is,

272
00:17:00,150 --> 00:17:01,510
we're gay.

273
00:17:05,310 --> 00:17:08,559
That's why I took the liberty of assuming
that bringing you, a woman, to Kuji's place...

274
00:17:08,560 --> 00:17:11,130
wouldn't be a problem.

275
00:17:12,110 --> 00:17:13,110
Or rather,

276
00:17:13,710 --> 00:17:15,600
I was being naive and inconsiderate.

277
00:17:18,910 --> 00:17:21,140
It's just that Kuji understands
everything about me,

278
00:17:21,170 --> 00:17:22,870
so I feel comfortable around him.

279
00:17:23,890 --> 00:17:25,240
I see.

280
00:17:26,350 --> 00:17:28,080
Now that I've told you all this,

281
00:17:28,440 --> 00:17:32,450
I feel like I might have just given you
an unnecessary burden.

282
00:17:32,580 --> 00:17:33,190
Not at all.

283
00:17:33,191 --> 00:17:34,250
That's not true.

284
00:17:36,030 --> 00:17:39,050
Kuji also said it would
be best to tell you.

285
00:17:40,090 --> 00:17:42,330
We're not trying to hide it.

286
00:17:42,870 --> 00:17:45,030
We just don't bring it up.

287
00:17:45,710 --> 00:17:48,030
Yes, I understand.

288
00:17:50,490 --> 00:17:53,500
Oh, this is my way.

289
00:17:54,050 --> 00:17:57,039
Okay, see you in class.

290
00:17:57,040 --> 00:17:58,040
Okay.

291
00:18:07,030 --> 00:18:09,950
Why am I only getting nervous now?

292
00:18:14,770 --> 00:18:15,770
Takechi!

293
00:18:16,170 --> 00:18:17,310
Azuma-san.

294
00:18:19,090 --> 00:18:20,090
I'm sorry.

295
00:18:20,370 --> 00:18:22,550
I haven't been in touch.

296
00:18:25,030 --> 00:18:26,030
I'm so glad.

297
00:18:26,390 --> 00:18:27,590
You were willing to come back.

298
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,270
I'm going to work hard here.

299
00:18:34,630 --> 00:18:35,580
Besides,

300
00:18:35,581 --> 00:18:38,780
there's nothing else
I can do for Tajimi-san.

301
00:18:42,530 --> 00:18:43,990
Let's do our best together.

302
00:18:48,570 --> 00:18:50,589
Here, this is from Hara-san for you.

303
00:18:50,590 --> 00:18:52,009
She said it's a thank you for last time.

304
00:18:52,010 --> 00:18:55,360
Oh, a Sendai specialty.
This stuff is delicious.

305
00:18:55,590 --> 00:18:56,810
Let's dig in, let's dig in.

306
00:18:57,400 --> 00:18:59,070
We'll need some beer to go with this.

307
00:19:00,550 --> 00:19:03,470
Oh, by the way, I've
decided to give it a try.

308
00:19:04,290 --> 00:19:05,570
The afterword essay.

309
00:19:05,840 --> 00:19:06,910
Oh?

310
00:19:07,290 --> 00:19:09,780
What, did the sun rise in the west?

311
00:19:11,650 --> 00:19:13,020
Looking back now,

312
00:19:14,890 --> 00:19:18,750
the reason my dad so readily agreed
to let me pursue translation as a career...

313
00:19:20,250 --> 00:19:23,630
was probably because he wanted to
leave something for me through his work.

314
00:19:27,250 --> 00:19:29,329
The only thing I can pass on...

315
00:19:29,330 --> 00:19:30,970
is that sentiment.

316
00:19:33,750 --> 00:19:36,000
Passing something on...

317
00:19:37,420 --> 00:19:38,510
Hm?

318
00:19:39,490 --> 00:19:40,740
It's nothing.

319
00:19:41,690 --> 00:19:45,350
So you'll be seeing that
handsome older guy a lot more?

320
00:19:45,390 --> 00:19:47,480
Using the essay as an excuse.

321
00:19:48,550 --> 00:19:50,690
It's not an excuse, it's work.

322
00:19:51,110 --> 00:19:52,450
Legitimate work.

323
00:19:53,410 --> 00:19:54,410
I know, I know.

324
00:19:57,090 --> 00:19:59,730
I'm not young enough to get the
wrong idea over something so silly.

325
00:20:01,070 --> 00:20:02,070
Right, right.

326
00:20:05,750 --> 00:20:06,750
But still,

327
00:20:07,750 --> 00:20:10,710
it's nice to have something to pass on.

328
00:20:12,810 --> 00:20:13,810
Yeah.

329
00:20:18,090 --> 00:20:19,090
Kuji.

330
00:20:20,190 --> 00:20:22,820
Have you ever thought
about getting married?

331
00:20:26,410 --> 00:20:27,410
Never.

332
00:20:28,890 --> 00:20:30,930
I hope same-sex marriage becomes legal,

333
00:20:32,290 --> 00:20:34,290
but I don't have the desire
to get married myself.

334
00:20:34,730 --> 00:20:36,200
Me neither.

335
00:20:38,650 --> 00:20:41,879
A comfortable distance,
a comfortable relationship.

336
00:20:41,880 --> 00:20:44,410
It's nice to be at ease.

337
00:20:44,840 --> 00:20:47,229
Is this what you call a
'comfortable distance'?

338
00:20:47,230 --> 00:20:48,230
Yeah.

339
00:20:49,590 --> 00:20:51,010
Stay by my side.

340
00:20:51,550 --> 00:20:52,550
You yeti.

341
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:56,390
What part of me is a yeti?

342
00:20:58,890 --> 00:21:00,990
Isn't there one in "Rex's Adventure"?

343
00:21:01,050 --> 00:21:02,820
The farewell with the yeti.

344
00:21:04,790 --> 00:21:07,100
Oh, right, that part.

345
00:21:08,850 --> 00:21:10,170
When I was a kid,

346
00:21:10,850 --> 00:21:13,849
I used to wish there were no goodbyes
and we could all stay together forever.

347
00:21:13,850 --> 00:21:16,010
I just suddenly remembered that.

348
00:21:17,390 --> 00:21:18,970
You can never see them again.

349
00:21:22,130 --> 00:21:23,810
You can never go back.

350
00:21:26,910 --> 00:21:30,290
I wonder if the future is just
an endless series of losses.

351
00:21:31,510 --> 00:21:33,390
Sometimes I suddenly think that.

352
00:21:35,370 --> 00:21:40,370
Time, people, and places.

353
00:21:42,910 --> 00:21:46,730
Someday, will you also...?

354
00:21:47,930 --> 00:21:49,040
Kuji.

355
00:21:50,470 --> 00:21:51,540
Hm?

356
00:21:52,670 --> 00:21:53,880
You know,

357
00:21:54,550 --> 00:21:57,210
I always want to be with you.

358
00:21:57,270 --> 00:21:58,580
With you, Kuji.

359
00:22:01,770 --> 00:22:02,770
Huh?

360
00:22:05,410 --> 00:22:06,690
Oh.

361
00:22:08,010 --> 00:22:09,290
Hey, why the sudden declaration?

362
00:22:10,690 --> 00:22:14,700
I just thought it's better
to say these things clearly.

363
00:22:17,270 --> 00:22:19,100
Well, thank you for the
special announcement.

364
00:22:22,050 --> 00:22:27,050
For the record, this isn't
a confession, it's a report.

365
00:22:31,270 --> 00:22:32,270
Is that so?

366
00:22:34,210 --> 00:22:36,890
Yeah. Message received.

367
00:22:42,710 --> 00:22:43,810
Connected hearts.

368
00:22:44,970 --> 00:22:46,070
Beyond that,

369
00:22:47,010 --> 00:22:49,260
I believe there must be something.

370
00:22:52,130 --> 00:22:54,619
Something that won't easily disappear.

371
00:22:54,620 --> 00:22:56,610
A place where I belong.

372
00:22:56,910 --> 00:22:58,990
What should we eat tomorrow?

373
00:23:00,100 --> 00:23:01,200
(Next episode)

374
00:23:01,230 --> 00:23:02,570
You can't be serious, Kuji.

375
00:23:02,670 --> 00:23:04,199
Competitions can be a matter of luck,

376
00:23:04,200 --> 00:23:05,829
but it's worth a shot.

377
00:23:05,830 --> 00:23:06,830
I'm counting on you.

378
00:23:06,910 --> 00:23:09,170
Always connecting people.

379
00:23:09,310 --> 00:23:10,870
I wish I could be someone like that.

380
00:23:11,930 --> 00:23:13,090
What are you spacing out for?

381
00:23:13,706 --> 00:23:15,076
You're so annoying.

